  </td>
  <td>
  <div id=3DPPTP2 class=3DPTxt><font size=3D2><a
  href=3D"javascript:GoToSld('slide0002.htm');" id=3DPPTL2>What is Programm=
ing?</a></font></div>
  <div id=3DPPTC2 class=3DCTxt style=3D'display:none'><font size=3D2>
  <ul>
   <li>It&#8217;s the way we can tell computers to do what we want.</li>
   <li>Whenever you use a computer, you run one or more programs.</li>
   <li>Examples: Internet Explorer, Microsoft Word, Photoshop</li>
   <li>You can also write your own programs using programming languages.</l=
i>
  </ul>
  </font></div>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr onmouseover=3D"Over(this)" onmouseout=3D"Out(this)" onclick=3D"Follow(=
this)"
  style=3D'cursor:hand'>
  <td align=3Dright valign=3Dtop>
  <div class=3DsldNum><font size=3D2>3</font></div>
  </td>
  <td>
  <div id=3DPPTP3 class=3DPTxt><font size=3D2><a
  href=3D"javascript:GoToSld('slide0003.htm');" id=3DPPTL3>Programming Lang=
uages</a></font></div>
  <div id=3DPPTC3 class=3DCTxt style=3D'display:none'><font size=3D2>
  <ul>
   <li>To tell the computer what to do, we need to speak a language that it
       understands. Such languages are called programming languages.</li>
   <li>Examples of programming languages:</li>
   <ul>
    <li>Logo</li>
    <li>Scheme</li>
    <li>C/C++</li>
    <li>BASIC</li>
    <li>Java</li>
   </ul>
  </ul>
  </font></div>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr onmouseover=3D"Over(this)" onmouseout=3D"Out(this)" onclick=3D"Follow(=
this)"
  style=3D'cursor:hand'>
  <td align=3Dright valign=3Dtop>
  <div class=3DsldNum><font size=3D2>4</font></div>
  </td>
  <td>
  <div id=3DPPTP4 class=3DPTxt><font size=3D2><a
  href=3D"javascript:GoToSld('slide0004.htm');" id=3DPPTL4>Human Language</=
a></font></div>
  <div id=3DPPTC4 class=3DCTxt style=3D'display:none'><font size=3D2>
  <ul>
   <li>When people talk, they often say things they don&#8217;t mean</li>
   <ul>
    <li>&#8220;It&#8217;s raining cats and dogs.&#8221;</li>
   </ul>
   <li>Humans are also vague.</li>
   <ul>
    <li>&#8220;Could you hand me that thing over there?&#8221;</li>
   </ul>
   <li>Computers can&#8217;t fill in what we&#8217;ve left out, so we have =
to
       be very clear.</li>
  </ul>
  </font></div>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr onmouseover=3D"Over(this)" onmouseout=3D"Out(this)" onclick=3D"Follow(=
this)"
  style=3D'cursor:hand'>
  <td align=3Dright valign=3Dtop>
  <div class=3DsldNum><font size=3D2>5</font></div>
  </td>
  <td>
  <div id=3DPPTP5 class=3DPTxt><font size=3D2><a
  href=3D"javascript:GoToSld('slide0005.htm');" id=3DPPTL5>Languages</a></f=
ont></div>
  <div id=3DPPTC5 class=3DCTxt style=3D'display:none'><font size=3D2>
  <ul>
   <li>All languages, both for humans and computers, have grammar and synta=
x.</li>
   <li>Grammar is the structure of the words in sentences or statements. It
       tells us what order words come in and what kinds of words go where.<=
/li>
   <li>Syntax is the punctuation of a language.</li>
   <ul>
    <li>Sarah youre&#8212;standing right? There: hand! me, that&#8212;marke=
r,</li>
    <li>If the syntax is wrong, things won&#8217;t make sense.</li>
   </ul>
  </ul>
  </font></div>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr onmouseover=3D"Over(this)" onmouseout=3D"Out(this)" onclick=3D"Follow(=
this)"
  style=3D'cursor:hand'>
  <td align=3Dright valign=3Dtop>
  <div class=3DsldNum><font size=3D2>6</font></div>
  </td>
  <td>
  <div id=3DPPTP6 class=3DPTxt><font size=3D2><a
  href=3D"javascript:GoToSld('slide0006.htm');" id=3DPPTL6>More on Grammar<=
/a></font></div>
  <div id=3DPPTC6 class=3DCTxt style=3D'display:none'><font size=3D2>
  <ul>
   <li>In English, we have different parts of speech, such as nouns, verbs,
       adjectives, adverbs, pronouns, and articles.</li>
   <li>In programming languages, we have parts of speech such as numbers,
       procedures (aka functions, subroutines, and methods), keywords, and
       strings of text.</li>
  </ul>
  </font></div>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr onmouseover=3D"Over(this)" onmouseout=3D"Out(this)" onclick=3D"Follow(=
this)"
  style=3D'cursor:hand'>
  <td align=3Dright valign=3Dtop>
  <div class=3DsldNum><font size=3D2>7</font></div>
  </td>
  <td>
  <div id=3DPPTP7 class=3DPTxt><font size=3D2><a
  href=3D"javascript:GoToSld('slide0007.htm');" id=3DPPTL7>Beyond Grammar</=
a></font></div>
  <div id=3DPPTC7 class=3DCTxt style=3D'display:none'><font size=3D2>
  <ul>
   <li>We have to have the grammar and syntax correct for the computer to
       understand us, but programming is much more than that.</li>
   <li>What&#8217;s most important is the algorithm.</li>
  </ul>
  </font></div>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr onmouseover=3D"Over(this)" onmouseout=3D"Out(this)" onclick=3D"Follow(=
this)"
  style=3D'cursor:hand'>
  <td align=3Dright valign=3Dtop>
  <div class=3DsldNum><font size=3D2>8</font></div>
  </td>
  <td>
  <div id=3DPPTP8 class=3DPTxt><font size=3D2><a
  href=3D"javascript:GoToSld('slide0008.htm');" id=3DPPTL8>Example Algorith=
ms</a></font></div>
  <div id=3DPPTC8 class=3DCTxt style=3D'display:none'><font size=3D2>
  <ul>
   <li>A recipe in a cookbook is an algorithm.</li>
   <ul>
    <li>Ingredients:</li>
    <ul>
     <li>1/2 cup of butter</li>
     <li>1 cup of white sugar</li>
     <li>2 eggs</li>
     <li>1 teaspoon of vanilla</li>
     <li>1/3 cup of cocoa</li>
     <li>3/4 cup of flour</li>
     <li>1/2 teaspoon of baking powder</li>
     <li>1/4 teaspoon of salt</li>
    </ul>
    <li>Directions:</li>
    <ul>
     <li>Mix butter and sugar and beat well until fluffy.</li>
     <li>Beat in the eggs and vanilla</li>
     <li>Sift cocoa with the flour, baking powder &amp; salt. Work into the
         creamed mixture.</li>
     <li>Spoon this into a 8x8x2 inch pan and bake for 30-35 minutes at 350
         degrees.</li>
    </ul>
   </ul>
  </ul>
  </font></div>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr onmouseover=3D"Over(this)" onmouseout=3D"Out(this)" onclick=3D"Follow(=
this)"
  style=3D'cursor:hand'>
  <td align=3Dright valign=3Dtop>
  <div class=3DsldNum><font size=3D2>9</font></div>
  </td>
  <td>
  <div id=3DPPTP9 class=3DPTxt><font size=3D2><a
  href=3D"javascript:GoToSld('slide0009.htm');" id=3DPPTL9>Example Algorith=
ms</a></font></div>
  <div id=3DPPTC9 class=3DCTxt style=3D'display:none'><font size=3D2>
  <ul>
   <li>To get to the CIT from 95:</li>
   <ul>
    <li>Take Exit 20 onto 195 East (Cape Cod).</li>
    <li>Take Exit 2 to WICKENDEN Street.</li>
    <li>Turn LEFT at the light on to WICKENDEN and LEFT at the 2nd light on=
 to
        BROOK St.</li>
    <li>Continue on Brook for several blocks to a traffic light.</li>
    <li>Our red brick building is on your left.</li>
    <li>The front of our building is on the other side, facing a quadrangle=
.</li>
   </ul>
  </ul>
  </font></div>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr onmouseover=3D"Over(this)" onmouseout=3D"Out(this)" onclick=3D"Follow(=
this)"
  style=3D'cursor:hand'>
  <td align=3Dright valign=3Dtop>
  <div class=3DsldNum><font size=3D2>10</font></div>
  </td>
  <td>
  <div id=3DPPTP10 class=3DPTxt><font size=3D2><a
  href=3D"javascript:GoToSld('slide0014.htm');" id=3DPPTL10>Procedures</a><=
/font></div>
  <div id=3DPPTC10 class=3DCTxt style=3D'display:none'><font size=3D2>
  <ul>
   <li>Once we&#8217;ve written a procedure, we can re-use it whenever we w=
ant.</li>
   <li>For example, say we defined a procedure for getting to Brook Street =
from
       95.</li>
   <li>Our directions now look like:</li>
   <ul>
    <li>From 95, get onto Brook Street.</li>
    <li>Continue on Brook for several blocks to a traffic light.</li>
    <li>Our red brick building is on your left.</li>
    <li>The front of our building is on the other side, facing a quadrangle=
.</li>
   </ul>
   <li>Is there anything we left out from these directions?</li>
  </ul>
  </font></div>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr onmouseover=3D"Over(this)" onmouseout=3D"Out(this)" onclick=3D"Follow(=
this)"
  style=3D'cursor:hand'>
  <td align=3Dright valign=3Dtop>
  <div class=3DsldNum><font size=3D2>11</font></div>
  </td>
  <td>
  <div id=3DPPTP11 class=3DPTxt><font size=3D2><a
  href=3D"javascript:GoToSld('slide0012.htm');" id=3DPPTL11>Back to Languag=
es</a></font></div>
  <div id=3DPPTC11 class=3DCTxt style=3D'display:none'><font size=3D2>
  <ul>
   <li>What do algorithms have to do with programming languages?</li>
   <li>Answer: An algorithm is a series of steps. A language is the way we
       describe these steps.</li>
  </ul>
  </font></div>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr onmouseover=3D"Over(this)" onmouseout=3D"Out(this)" onclick=3D"Follow(=
this)"
  style=3D'cursor:hand'>
  <td align=3Dright valign=3Dtop>
  <div class=3DsldNum><font size=3D2>12</font></div>
  </td>
  <td>
  <div id=3DPPTP12 class=3DPTxt><font size=3D2><a
  href=3D"javascript:GoToSld('slide0013.htm');" id=3DPPTL12>Parameters</a><=
/font></div>
  <div id=3DPPTC12 class=3DCTxt style=3D'display:none'><font size=3D2>
  <ul>
   <li>Suppose we want to write an algorithm for making cookies, but we
       don&#8217;t know how many to make.</li>
   <li>We can generalize our algorithm with parameters (also called argumen=
ts).</li>
   <li>Can you think of a place where you&#8217;ve seen parameters before?<=
/li>
  </ul>
  </font></div>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr onmouseover=3D"Over(this)" onmouseout=3D"Out(this)" onclick=3D"Follow(=
this)"
  style=3D'cursor:hand'>
  <td align=3Dright valign=3Dtop>
  <div class=3DsldNum><font size=3D2>13</font></div>
  </td>
  <td>
  <div id=3DPPTP13 class=3DPTxt><font size=3D2><a
  href=3D"javascript:GoToSld('slide0010.htm');" id=3DPPTL13>Making Your Own=
</a></font></div>
  <div id=3DPPTC13 class=3DCTxt style=3D'display:none'><font size=3D2>
  <ul>
   <li>When you write your own algorithm, think about what steps you need to
       take.</li>
   <ul>
    <li>What order should they come in?</li>
   </ul>
   <li>Be careful not to leave anything out.</li>
  </ul>
  </font></div>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr onmouseover=3D"Over(this)" onmouseout=3D"Out(this)" onclick=3D"Follow(=
this)"
  style=3D'cursor:hand'>
  <td align=3Dright valign=3Dtop>
  <div class=3DsldNum><font size=3D2>14</font></div>
  </td>
  <td>
  <div id=3DPPTP14 class=3DPTxt><font size=3D2><a
  href=3D"javascript:GoToSld('slide0011.htm');" id=3DPPTL14>Ice Cream Sunda=
es</a></font></div>
  <div id=3DPPTC14 class=3DCTxt style=3D'display:none'><font size=3D2>
  <ul>
   <li>Your job now is to write an algorithm for making an ice cream sundae=
.</li>
   <li>What are the different steps you&#8217;ll want in your language?</li>
   <li>Write your algorithm down on paper. We&#8217;ll be collecting your
       algorithms.</li>
  </ul>
  </font></div>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>



